 ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Horton was born in 1203, in Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales as the daughter of Sir Philip Horton. She married William Picton in Pembrokeshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales."},"et":{"1203–":"1203–Surnud","1203–Female":"1203–Surnud","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1305":"1305","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1365":"1365","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1265":"1265","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Granston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembroke, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1203–":"1203–Kuollut","1203–Female":"1203–Kuollut","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1